been reinforced in Britain and Ireland by Huguenot bearers of the name <i>Roussel</i>, of the same Old French origin.","English: habitational name from any of several places called Rushall (Norfolk, Staffordshire, Wiltshire) or possibly sometimes from Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent). Rushall in Staffordshire derives from Old English <i>rysc</i> ‘rush, rushes’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’. Rushall in Norfolk derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>halh</i>. Rushall in Wiltshire derives from an Old English personal name <i>Rust</i> (genitive <i>Rustes</i>) + <i>halh</i>. Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent) probably derives from Old English <i>rust</i> ‘rust, rust color’ + <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’, but with a change in the final element due to influence from Middle English, Old English <i>hall</i> ‘hall, residence’, perhaps referring to a nearby building.","Americanized form of German <b>Rüssel</b>, from a pet form of any of various personal names formed with the element <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Russler","meanings":["German (<b>Rüssler</b>):","occupational name for a farmer, from an agent derivative of <i>rüsseln</i> ‘to shallow plow’.","variant of <b>Rüssel</b> (see   Russell   2)."]},{"name":"Rouse","meanings":["English: nickname for a person with red hair or a ruddy complexion, from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French <i>rous(e)</i> ‘red(-haired)’ (from Latin <i>russ(e)us</i>).","Americanized form of German   Raus  .","Walloon and northern French (<b>Rousé</b>): variant of <b>Rosé</b> (see   Rose  )."]},{"name":"Russel","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Russell  .","German: from a pet form of <i>Russ</i>, see   Russ   2.","northwest German (<b>Rüssel</b>): probably a variant of   Rossel  ."]}]},{"name":"Stephen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephan","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , preserving the vowels of the Greek name."]},{"name":"Steven","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , reflecting the normal pronunciation of the name in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Stephen Russell was born about 1335, in Strensham, Worcestershire, England, his father, William Russell, was 25 and his mother, heiress of Muschamp, was 22. He married Alice de la Tour in 1400, in Weymouth, Dorset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1438, in Weymouth, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 104."},"et":{"about 1335–1438":"umbes 1335–1438","1335–1438":"1335–1438","1385–1451":"1385–1451","1401–1463":"1401–1463","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1312–1340":"1312–1340","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1451":"1451","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Abt 1415":"umbes 1415","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1463":"1463","about 1335":"umbes 1335","about 1401":"umbes 